title:
An analogue of the Milnor conjecture for the de Rham-Witt complex in
  characteristic 2

sections.text:
#### Abstract

We describe the modulo 2 de Rham-Witt complex of a field of characteristic 2, in terms of the powers of the augmentation ideal of the $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-geometric fixed points of real topological restriction homology TRR. This is analogous to the conjecture of Milnor, proved in [Kat82] for fields of characteristic 2, which describes the modulo 2 Milnor K-theory in terms of the powers of the augmentation ideal of the Witt group of symmetric forms. Our proof provides a somewhat explicit description of these objects, as well as a calculation of the homotopy groups of the geometric fixed points of TRR and of real topological cyclic homology, for all fields.

## Introduction

Let $k$ be a field. Let us recall that Milnor conjectured, in [Mil71], [Mil70], that a certain canonical map of graded rings

$$
\mathrm{K}_{*}^{M}(k) / 2 \longrightarrow I^{*} / I^{*+1}
$$

should be an isomorphism. Here $\mathrm{K}_{*}^{M}(k)$ is the Milnor K-theory of $k$, and $I:=\operatorname{ker}\left(r k: \mathrm{W}^{*}(k) \rightarrow\right.$ $\mathbb{Z} / 2$ ) is the augmentation ideal of the Witt group $\mathrm{W}^{*}(k)$ of symmetric forms over $k$. This conjecture was proved in [Kat82] when $k$ has characteristic 2, and subsequently in [OVV07, Voe03, Mor05] in characteristic different from 2.

The starting point of our paper is the following, somewhat overloaded observation. On one side of this isomorphism, we have a "symbolic version" $\mathrm{K}_{*}^{M}(k)$ of the algebraic K-theory spectrum $\mathrm{K}(k)$ of $k$. On the other side, we have the Witt group $\mathrm{W}^{*}(k)$, which is $\pi_{0}$ of the $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-geometric fixed-points spectrum of a certain canonical $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-equivariant refinement $\mathrm{KR}(k)$ of $\mathrm{K}(k)$ (see $\left[\mathrm{CDH}^{*} 20 \mathrm{a}, \mathrm{CDH}^{*} 20 \mathrm{~b}\right]$ ). One may then wonder if a similar relationship holds for other functors closely related to algebraic K-theory. One does not need to look far for another such example, which is already provided in Kato's proof of Milnor's conjecture in characteristic 2: The de Rham complex $\Omega_{k}^{*}$ is a "symbolic version" of the topological Hochschild homology spectrum $\operatorname{THH}(k)$, and $\operatorname{THH}(k)$ also admits a canonical $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-equivariant refinement $\operatorname{THR}(k)$. The calculation of [DMPR21, Corollary 5.2] provides an isomorphism between $\pi_{0}$ of the $\mathbb{Z} / 2$ geometric fixed points of this spectrum and $\left(k \otimes_{S} k\right) / 2$, where $S \leq k$ is the subfield generated by the squares. The result analogous to Milnor's conjecture is then an isomorphism

$$
\Omega_{k}^{*} / 2 \xrightarrow{\circ} J^{*} / J^{*+1}
$$

where $J$ is the kernel of the multiplication map $\mu:\left(k \otimes_{S} k\right) / 2 \rightarrow k / 2$. Let us point out that, if 2 is a unit in $k$, the source and target of this map are clearly zero, so that this statement has content only when the characteristic of $k$ is 2 . It seems to be a standard result that this map is an isomorphism, and it plays an important role in the proof of [Kat82, Lemma 7(3)] (see [Ara20] for a proof, which we recast in Lemma 3.6). The main goal of our paper is to establish an analogous result for topological restriction homology, whose "symbolic version" is the de Rham-Witt complex of Bloch, Deligne and Illusie [Ill79].

Let $\mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)} \Omega_{k}^{*}$ be the 2 -typical de Rham-Witt complex of $k$. We will take the definition of [Cos08], as the initial object in the category of 2-typical Witt complexes over $k$ (see also [HM04]). For all integer $n \geq 0$, let $\mathrm{TR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)$ be the 2-typical $(n+1)$-truncated topological restriction homology of [BHM93] (see also [AN21]). Similarly to the relation between Milnor K-theory and algebraic K-theory, $\mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)} \Omega_{k}^{*}$ and the homotopy groups of $\mathrm{TR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)$ agree in low degrees, and the former should be consider the symbolic version of the latter (see [Hes04] and [GH99, §4]). We recall that the spectrum $\mathrm{TR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)$ is defined as the $C_{2^{n}}$-fixed points of a $C_{2^{n}}$-equivariant structure on $\operatorname{THH}(k)$, where $C_{2^{n}}$ is the cyclic group of order $2^{n}$. This admits a $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-equivariant refinement $\operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)$, constructed by extending the $C_{2^{n}}$-equivariant structure on $\operatorname{THH}(k)$ to an equivariant spectrum $\operatorname{THR}(k)$ for the dihedral group $D_{2^{n}}$ of order $2^{n+1}$. The fixed-point spectrum

$$
\operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2):=\operatorname{THR}(k)^{C_{2^{n}}}
$$

then inherits the structure of a $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-spectrum, since $\mathbb{Z} / 2$ is the Weyl group of $C_{2^{n}}$ in $D_{2^{n}}$. This construction is carried out in [Høg16] and [DMP24, §1], and we review it in $\S 1$. There is then a canonical ring homomorphism

$$
\operatorname{res}_{C_{2^{n}}}^{D_{2^{n}}}: \pi_{0} \operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\# \mathbb{Z} / 2} \longrightarrow \pi_{0} \operatorname{TR}^{n+1}(k ; 2) / 2
$$

where $(-)^{\# \mathbb{Z} / 2}$ denotes the geometric fixed-points functor, and we let $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}$ be its kernel. There are operators between these spectra

$$
\operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\# \mathbb{Z} / 2} \underset{F}{\stackrel{R}{\longrightarrow}} \operatorname{TRR}^{n}(k ; 2)^{\# \mathbb{Z} / 2}
$$

which correspond to the usual respective maps $R, V$ and $F$ on $\operatorname{TR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)$ under the restriction map above. There is also a map

$$
\sigma: \operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\# \mathbb{Z} / 2} \longrightarrow \operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\# \mathbb{Z} / 2}
$$

of order 2, which is induced by the action of the Weyl group of $\mathbb{Z} / 2$ in the quotient $D_{2^{n+1}} / C_{2^{n}}$. It is easy to see that all these maps restrict to maps between the kernels $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}$. The main result of the paper is the following analogue of Milnor's conjecture.
Theorem A. Let $k$ be a field of characteristic 2. The maps $R, F, V$ and $d:=1+\sigma$ endow the sequence $J_{(2 \bullet)}^{*} / J_{(2 \bullet)}^{n+1}$ with the structure of a 2-typical Witt complex over $k$, and the unique map of 2-typical Witt complexes over $k$

$$
\left(\mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)} \Omega_{k}^{*}\right) / 2 \longrightarrow J_{(2 \bullet)}^{*} / J_{(2 \bullet)}^{n+1}
$$

is a strict isomorphism.
Let us remark on some special cases of this theorem:
i) For $*=0$, the isomorphism of Theorem A identifies with the modulo 2 reduction of the isomorphism $\mathrm{W}_{(2^{n})}(k) \cong \pi_{0} \mathrm{TR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)$ of [HM97, Theorem F], where $\mathrm{W}_{(2^{n})}(k)$ is the ring of $(n+1)$-truncated 2-typical Witt vectors of $k$.
ii) For $\bullet=0$, the isomorphism of Theorem A is the isomorphism $\Omega_{k}^{*} \cong J^{*} / J^{*+1}$ discussed above.
iii) If $k$ has characteristic different from 2 , then both $\left(\mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)} \Omega_{k}^{*}\right) / 2$ and $\operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\# \mathbb{Z} / 2}$ vanish, so Theorem A in fact holds in all characteristics.
iv) If $k$ is perfect of characteristic 2 , then $\left(\mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)} \Omega_{k}^{*}\right) / 2=0$ for $*=0$, and

$$
\left(\mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)} \Omega_{k}^{0}\right) / 2=\mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)}(k) / 2 \cong k
$$

Similarly, in the case of perfect fields, $\pi_{0} \operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\# \mathbb{Z} / 2} \cong k$ and $J_{(2 \bullet)}=0$ (see [DMP24, Theorem 4.7]). Thus, Theorem A has non-trivial content only for non-perfect fields of characteristic 2 .

We prove the theorem by first explicitly calculating the homotopy groups of $\operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$ in $\S 2.1$ (even though we really only need $\pi_{0}$ ), extending the calculations for perfect fields of [DMP24, §4.2]. We then use our calculation to provide generators for $\pi_{0} \operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$ and $J_{\left(2^{*}\right)}$, analogous to the canonical generators $V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a)$ of the Witt vectors (see Propositions 2.9 and 2.16). This allows us to define a Witt-complex structure on $J_{(2^{*})}^{*} / J_{(2^{*})}^{n+1}$, and to prove Theorem A by induction on $\bullet$, using the exact sequences of [Cos08, Lemma 3.5], in $\S 3.2$.

The description of the homotopy groups of $\operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$ is in Theorem 2.7, and it is proved using the pullbacks of [DMP24, Theorem 2.7]. It is somewhat technical, and we won't state it here, but it is completely explicit. There is however a closely related calculation which is more straightforward to state. Let $\operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)$ be the 2 -typical real topological cyclic homology spectrum of $k$, which we may define as the equaliser

$$
\operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2):=e q\left(\operatorname{TRR}(k ; 2) \stackrel{\text { id }}{\stackrel{\text { iid }}{\rightleftarrows}} \operatorname{TRR}(k ; 2)\right)
$$

where $\operatorname{TRR}(k ; 2)$ is the limit of $\operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)$ over the maps $R$. Let us point out that, by [DMP24, Theorem A], if 2 is a unit in $k$, then $\operatorname{TCR}(k ; p)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}=0$ for every prime $p$, so that we may assume that $k$ has characteristic 2 . Let $C_{2}$ act on $k \otimes_{S} k$ by swapping the two tensor factors, where $S \leq k$ is the subfield of squares. Let us denote by $w$ the generator of $C_{2}$. The following is proved in Corollary 2.5.
Theorem B. Let $k$ be a field of characteristic 2. For every integer $l \geq 0$, there is an exact sequence

$$
0 \rightarrow \pi_{2 l} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \rightarrow\left(k \otimes_{S} k\right)^{C_{2}} \xrightarrow{w-\phi}\left(k \otimes_{S} k\right)^{C_{2}} / \operatorname{Im}(1+w) \rightarrow \pi_{2 l-1} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \rightarrow 0
$$

where $\pi$ is the quotient map, and $\phi$ is the ring homomorphism defined by $\phi(a \otimes b)=b a^{2} \otimes b$.
The map $\phi$ in fact determines an isomorphism $\phi: k \otimes_{S} k \rightarrow\left(k \otimes_{S} k\right)^{C_{2}} / \operatorname{Im}(1+w)$, and is in a sense a replacement of the Frobenius of $k$ when $k$ is not perfect (see Lemma 2.1). It plays a crucial role in the calculations of $\S 2.1$ and in the description of $J_{\left(2^{*}\right)}$.

In [Kat82, Theorem (1)], Kato exhibits a closely related exact sequence, involving the symmetric and quadratic Witt groups $\mathrm{W}^{s}(k)$ and $\mathrm{W}^{q}(k)$. Combined with Theorem B, it gives isomorphisms

$$
\pi_{2 l} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \cong \mathrm{~W}^{s}(k) \quad \text { and } \quad \pi_{2 l-1} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \cong \mathrm{~W}^{q}(k)
$$

for every $l \geq 0$. In fact, this identifies the homotopy groups of $\operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$ with the genuine normal L-groups of $k$, as conjectured by Nikolaus, proved in great generality in [HNS21], and verified in [DMP24] in the case of perfect fields (see Remark 2.6).

From Theorem B, we can also deduce a version of the Milnor conjecture for TC. Let us choose the respective equaliser and coequaliser

$$
\nu_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2) \longrightarrow\left(\mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{m}\right)} \Omega_{k}^{*}\right) / 2 \xrightarrow[\digamma]{\stackrel{\text { id }}{\longrightarrow}}\left(\mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{m}\right)} \Omega_{k}^{*}\right) / 2 \longrightarrow \epsilon_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2)
$$

as possible symbolic versions of topological cyclic homology modulo 2 , where $\mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{m}\right)} \Omega_{k}^{*}$ is the limit over the map $R$ of $\mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{*}\right)} \Omega_{k}^{*}$ (and we are intentionally quotienting out 2 before taking the equaliser). Now let

$$
K:=\operatorname{ker}\left(\operatorname{res}_{c}^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}: \pi_{0} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \longrightarrow\left(\pi_{0} \operatorname{TC}(k ; 2)\right)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2} / \operatorname{Im}(1+w)\right)
$$

be the kernel of the restriction map, where $w$ is the involution on $\pi_{0} \mathrm{TC}(k ; 2)$ induced from the $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-action on $\operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)$. Let us also denote $T_{-1}:=\pi_{-1} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$, which we consider as a $\pi_{0} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$-module. The following is a TC analogue of [Kat82, Theorem (2)].

Corollary C. For every field $k$ of characteristic 2, there is an isomorphism of graded rings

$$
\nu_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2) \cong K^{*} / K^{*+1}
$$

and an isomorphism of graded $K^{*} / K^{*+1}$-modules

$$
\epsilon_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2) \cong K^{*} T_{-1} / K^{*+1} T_{-1}
$$

We prove this result in $\S 3.3$. Our argument is fairly straightforward, but relies on the Milnor conjecture at the prime 2 and on the identification from [CMM21, Proposition 2.26] of $\nu_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2)$ and $\epsilon_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2)$ with the respective equaliser and coequaliser

$$
\nu^{*}(k) \longrightarrow \Omega_{k}^{*} \xrightarrow[C^{-1}]{x} \Omega_{k}^{*} / d\left(\Omega_{k}^{*-1}\right) \longrightarrow \epsilon^{*}(k)
$$

of the projection $\pi$ and the inverse Cartier operator $C^{-1}$. We then use Theorem B to compare $K$ with the augmentation ideal $I$ of the Witt group $\mathrm{W}^{*}(k)$. In order to carry out this last step, we need to understand the restriction map of $\pi_{0} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\circ \mathbb{Z} / 2}$. We are unable to do this directly, and we need to employ the existence of a trace map of $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-equivariant spectra from the real algebraic K-theory spectrum $\operatorname{tr}: \mathrm{KR}(k) \rightarrow \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)$, which lifts the K-theoretic trace of [BHM93] and which has a certain effect on $\pi_{0}$. This map will appear in forthcoming work of Harpaz-Nikolaus-Shah [HNS21] in the framework of real K-theory of Poincaré $\infty$-categories. For completeness, we will give a construction in Appendix §A for rings with involution $A$, by lifting the trace map of $[\mathrm{DO} 19]$ from $\operatorname{THR}(A)$ to $\operatorname{TCR}(A ; p)$.
Theorem D. Let $A$ be a ring with involution. For every prime $p$, there is a map of $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-spectra $\operatorname{tr}: \mathrm{KR}(A) \rightarrow \operatorname{TCR}(A ; p)$ which forgets to the $K$-theoretic trace map of [BHM93]. The composite

$$
\mathrm{GW}^{*}(A)=\pi_{0}\left(\mathrm{KR}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right) \xrightarrow{\operatorname{tr}} \pi_{0}\left(\operatorname{TCR}(A ; 2)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right) \xrightarrow{R} \pi_{0}\left(\operatorname{THR}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right) \cong\left(A^{\mathbb{Z} / 2} \otimes A^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right) / T
$$

sends the element of the Grothendieck-Witt group $\mathrm{GW}^{*}(A)$ represented by a symmetric form $x$ on the free module $A^{\otimes n}$ to

$$
\operatorname{tr}(x)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\left(x^{-1}\right)_{i i} \otimes x_{i i}-\left(x^{-1}\right)_{i i} x_{i i} \otimes 1\right)+n \otimes 1
$$

where $x_{i i}$ are the diagonal entries of the matrix of $x$ for the standard basis of $A^{\otimes n}$, and $x^{-1}$ denotes the inverse matrix. Here the isomorphism describing $\pi_{0}\left(\operatorname{THR}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right)$ is from [DMPR21, Theorem 5.1].

# 1 Preliminaries on real topological Hochschild homology 

Here we recall the basic definitions surrounding real topological cyclic homology. In order to streamline this section, we recast the definitions in the special case where the input is a discrete commutative ring $A$ with the trivial involution (which in the next sections of the paper will be a field $k$ of characteristic 2). We refer the details of these constructions to [DMPR21] and [DMP24], and we will freely use the language of stable equivariant homotopy theory.

Let $O(2)$ be the infinite dihedral group, that we identify with the semi-direct product $\mathbb{Z} / 2 \rtimes S^{1}$ by choosing the reflection across the real axis as the generator for $\mathbb{Z} / 2$. The real topological Hochschild homology of $A$ is a ring $O(2)$-spectrum $\operatorname{THR}(A)$, whose underlying ring $S^{1}$-spectrum is the topological Hochschild homology spectrum $\operatorname{THH}(A)$, originally defined in [Bök86] (see also [BHM93] and [NS18]). It can be constructed, as an $O(2)$-equivariant ring orthogonal spectrum, as the geometric realisation of the dihedral bar construction

$$
\operatorname{THR}(A):=\left|N^{d i} \mathrm{H} A\right|=|[n] \mapsto(\mathrm{H} A)^{\otimes n+1} \mid
$$

where $\mathrm{H} A$ is (a flat model for) the Eilenberg-MacLane ring orthogonal $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-spectrum of $A$, and $\otimes$ denotes the smash product of spectra (see [DMPR21]). The action of $O(2)$ is defined from the structure of a dihedral object in the sense of [FL91, S 1.5, Example 5] and [Lod87], where the cyclic group $C_{n+1}$ acts in simplicial degree $n$ by rotating the $n+1$ smash factors, and the reflection acts in degree $n$ by reversing the order of the last $n$ smash factors.

Now let $p$ be a prime, $n \geq 0$ an integer, and $D_{p^{n}}=\mathbb{Z} / 2 \rtimes C_{p^{n}}$ the finite dihedral subgroup of $O(2)$ of order $2 p^{n}$. Since the Weyl group of $C_{p^{n}}$ inside $D_{p^{n}}$ is $\mathbb{Z} / 2$, the (genuine) fixed-points ring spectrum $\operatorname{THR}(A)^{C_{p^{n}}}$ is canonically a ring $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-spectrum. The inclusion of subgroups $C_{p^{n-1}} \leq C_{p^{n}}$ induces a restriction map $F$, also called Frobenius, and a transfer map $V$, also called Verschiebung, which are maps of $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-spectra

$$
\operatorname{THR}(A)^{C_{p^{n}}} \stackrel{F}{\longleftrightarrow} \operatorname{THR}(A)^{C_{p^{n-1}}}
$$

There is a further map $R$ of $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-spectra, sometimes called restriction or truncation

$$
\operatorname{THR}(A)^{C_{p^{n}}} \xrightarrow{R} \operatorname{THR}(A)^{C_{p^{n-1}}}
$$

which is defined from the real cyclotomic structure of $\operatorname{THR}(A)$ (see [DPM22, Definition 3.9]). The maps $R$ and $F$ are moreover maps of ring spectra (see [DPM22, Remark 3.10]). On underlying spectra, these are the maps $F, V$ and $R$ of $\operatorname{THH}(A)$, which after applying $\pi_{0}$ correspond to the operators on the ring of Witt vectors with the same name, see [HM97, Theorem 3.3].

Definition 1.1. Let $A$ be a commutative ring, and $p$ a prime. The $p$-typical truncated real topological restriction homology, real topological restriction homology, and real topological cyclic homology of $A$ are the ring $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-spectra defined respectively as:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(A ; p):=\operatorname{THR}(A)^{C_{p^{n}}} \\
& \operatorname{TRR}(A ; p):=\lim \left(\ldots \xrightarrow{R} \operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(A ; p) \xrightarrow{R} \operatorname{TRR}^{n}(A ; p) \xrightarrow{R} \ldots \xrightarrow{R} \operatorname{TRR}^{1}(A ; p)=\operatorname{THR}(A)\right) \\
& \operatorname{TCR}(A ; p):=e q\left(\operatorname{TRR}(A ; p) \xrightarrow[F]{i d} \operatorname{TRR}(A ; p)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where the map $F$ in the equaliser is induced by the Frobenius maps above, since $R$ and $F$ commute.

The $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-geometric fixed points of these spectra are characterised in [DMP24], as we now recall. These results will be used in $\S 2.1$ below, and we encourage the reader, at least for the purpose of the present paper, to take them as definitions of these objects.

In [DMP24, §1.2], we give a canonical equivalence of ring spectra

$$
\operatorname{THR}(A)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}=\operatorname{TRR}^{1}(A ; p)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \simeq(\mathrm{H} \underline{A})^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \otimes_{\mathrm{H} A}(\mathrm{H} \underline{A})^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}
$$

where $\mathrm{H} \underline{A}$ is the Eilenberg MacLane spectrum of the $\mathbb{Z} / 2$ Mackey functor (or Tambara functor) with constant value $A$ and transfer map 2. Its geometric fixed-points spectrum is then regarded as an $\mathrm{H} A$-module via the map of ring spectra

$$
\mathrm{H} A \simeq\left(N_{e}^{\mathbb{Z} / 2} \mathrm{H} A\right)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \xrightarrow{e^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}}(\mathrm{H} \underline{A})^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}
$$

where $N_{e}^{\mathbb{Z} / 2} \mathrm{H} A$ is the Hill-Hopkins-Ravenel norm construction of the ring spectrum $\mathrm{H} A$ of [HHR16] and [Sto11], and $\epsilon$ is the counit of the free-forgetful adjunction between commutative ring $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-spectra and commutative ring spectra. We will call this the Frobenius module structure of $(\mathrm{H} \underline{A})^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$, and refer to [DMPR21, §2.5] for the details of its construction. The Weyl group of $\mathbb{Z} / 2$ in $D_{2}=\mathbb{Z} / 2 \times C_{2}$ is $C_{2}$, and therefore $\operatorname{THR}(A)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$ is canonically a ring $C_{2}$-spectrum. In [DMP24, Lemma 1.2], we lift the equivalence above to an equivalence of ring $C_{2}$-spectra

$$
\operatorname{THR}(A)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \simeq \mathrm{H} \underline{A} \otimes_{N_{e}^{C_{2}} \mathrm{H} A} N_{e}^{C_{2}}\left((\mathrm{H} \underline{A})^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}\right)
$$

where the right factor is a module by applying the norm to the map $\mathrm{H} A \rightarrow(\mathrm{H} \underline{A})^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$, and the left factor is now regarded as a $C_{2}$-spectrum.

This $C_{2}$-equivariant homotopy type will help us characterise the $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-geometric fixed points of $\operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(A ; p)$, inductively on $n$. For every $n \geq 1$, the $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-geometric fixed points of $\operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(A ; p)$ is equivalent to the product of $(n+1)$-copies of $\operatorname{THR}(A)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$ if $p$ is odd, see [DMP24, Theorem 2.1]. For $p=2$, they are given by a pullback of ring spectra

see [DMP24, Theorem 2.7]. Here $\sigma_{n}$ is the generator of the Weyl group of $\mathbb{Z} / 2$ inside the quotient $D_{2^{n}} / C_{2^{n-1}}$, which is also of order 2 . The map

$$
\curvearrowleft(\operatorname{THR}(A)^{C_{2}})^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \longrightarrow(\operatorname{THR}(A)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2})^{C_{2}}
$$

is a certain canonical map, and $r$ is the canonical map to the $C_{2}$-geometric fixed points followed by the equivalence given by the cyclotomic structure (see above [DMP24, Theorem 2.7] for the definitions).

In [DMP24, Theorem A], we also characterise the real topological cyclic homology of $A$, by providing an equivalence of ring spectra

$$
\operatorname{TCR}(A ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}=\left(\left(\operatorname{THR}(A)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}\right)^{C_{2}} \xrightarrow[f]{r]{\stackrel{r}{\longrightarrow}} \operatorname{THR}(A)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}\right)
$$

where $f$ is the forgetful map.
Finally, we will need to briefly use the existence of norm maps on $\operatorname{THR}(A)$ in order calculate a certain restriction map, in Propositions 2.12 and 2.14. To establish their existence, we simply observe that the dihedral bar construction employed above to define THR has a canonical symmetric monoidal structure, and therefore $\operatorname{THR}(A)$ is a strictly commutative $O(2)$-equivariant ring spectrum (provided we choose a strictly commutative and flat model for the EilenbergMacLane ring $C_{2}$-spectrum $\mathrm{H} \underline{A}$, which we can achieve by a cofibrant replacement in the flat model structure of [Sto11, BDS16]). Thus, we obtain non-additive norm maps

$$
N_{H}^{G}: \pi_{0} \operatorname{THR}(A)^{H} \longrightarrow \pi_{0} \operatorname{THR}(A)^{G}
$$

for every pair of finite subgroups $H \leq G \leq O(2)$, which, when composed with a restriction map, satisfy the multiplicative double-coset formula.

# 2 Real TR and real TC of fields of characteristic 2
### 2.1 The geometric fixed points of TRR and TCR for fields of characteristic 2

Let $k$ be a field of characteristic 2 , and $S \leq k$ the subfield of squares. We regard $k$ as an $S$-vector space, and endow the abelian group $k \otimes_{S} k$ with the involution $w$ which flips the two tensor factors.

The homotopy groups of $\operatorname{TRR}(k)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$ have been computed in [DMP24, Theorem 4.7, Corollary 4.8] when the field $k$ is perfect, as a sum of copies of $k$. In this section we give an analogous description of these homotopy groups for a general field of characteristic 2 (and an analogous proof), where some of the copies of $k$ appearing in the calculation for perfect fields are replaced by expressions involving $k \otimes_{S} k$ (which is isomorphic to $k$ if $k$ is perfect). This is Theorem 2.7 below, and its statement and proof will be the content of $\S 2.1$.

The key algebraic input for extending the calculation to non-perfect fields lies in the following Lemma, which we will use several times throughout the paper. For every elementary tensor $a \otimes b \in k \otimes_{S} k$, let us define

$$

# 2.3 The fundamental ideal of TRR 

The components of the geometric fixed points of any connective $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-spectrum $X$ admit a restriction map, defined as the canonical map of cokernels
![img-11.jpeg](img-11.jpeg)

where $w$ is the action of the generator of $\mathbb{Z} / 2$ on $\pi_{0} X$. This map is moreover a monoidal natural transformation. By applying this construction to the $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-spectrum $\operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)$, we obtain a ring homomorphism which we denote by

$$
\operatorname{res}_{C_{2^{n}}}^{D_{2^{n}}}: \pi_{0} \operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \longrightarrow\left(\pi_{0} \operatorname{TR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)\right)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2} /(1+w) \cong \mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{n}\right)}(k) / 2
$$

Here $\mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{n}\right)}(k)$ is the ring of $(n+1)$-truncated 2-typical Witt vectors of $k$, and the isomorphism is from [HM97, Theorem F]. Here we use that the isomorphism of [HM97, Theorem F] is $\mathbb{Z} / 2$ equivariant, where the $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-action on $\mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{n}\right)}(k)$ is trivial (see the proof of [DPM22, Theorem 3.7], where the first paragraph of page 522 holds also for $p=2$. This can more generally be applied to the case where $k$ has a non-trivial involution, in which case the involution on $\pi_{0} \mathrm{TR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)$ corresponds to the map induced on $\mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{n}\right)}(k)$ by the involution on $k$ under the functoriality of the Witt vectors).

The goal of this section is to describe explicitly the map $\operatorname{res}_{C_{2^{n}}}^{D_{2^{n}}}$ under the isomorphism of Theorem 2.7, and provide generators for its kernel. We recall that for every commutative ring $R$, as a set, $\mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{n}\right)}(R)=R^{* n+1}$, with the unique functorial ring structure which makes the Witt polynomials into ring homomorphisms. For any $\mathbb{F}_{2}$-algebra $R$, we moreover have that as a set

$$
\mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{n}\right)}(R)=R \times\left(R / R^{2}\right)^{* n}
$$

We denote by $V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a)=(0, \ldots, 0, a, 0, \ldots, 0)$ the canonical additive generators of $\mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{n}\right)}(R)$, for $a \in R$.
Proposition 2.14. Let $k$ be a field of characteristic 2, and $n \geq 1$. Under the isomorphisms of Theorem 2.7 and [HM97, Theorem F], the restriction map corresponds to the unique ring homomorphism

$$
\operatorname{res}_{C_{2^{n}}}^{D_{2^{n}}}: \phi^{n-1}\left(\left(k \otimes_{S} k\right)^{C_{2}}\right) \underset{k \otimes_{S} k}{\times} \phi^{n-1}\left(\left(k \otimes_{S} k\right)^{C_{2}}\right) \longrightarrow \mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{n}\right)}(k) / 2
$$

which sends the respective generators of Proposition 2.9 to

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
\operatorname{res}_{C_{2^{n}}}^{D_{2^{n}}} \tau_{n}(a \otimes b) & =(a b, 0, \ldots, 0)=\tau_{n}(a b) \\
\operatorname{res}_{C_{2^{n}}}^{D_{2^{n}}} V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b) & =(0, \ldots, 0,[a b], 0, \ldots, 0)=\left[V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a b)\right] \\
\operatorname{res}_{C_{2^{n}}}^{D_{2^{n}}} \sigma V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b) & =(0, \ldots, 0,[a b], 0, \ldots, 0)=\left[V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a b)\right]
\end{array}
$$

for all $0 \leq i \leq n-1$, where the mod $k^{2}$ reduction $[a b]$ of ab sits in the $(n-i+1)$-st component.
Proof. Since $\pi_{0} \operatorname{THR}(k)$ is a $D_{2^{n}}$-Tambara functor, the restriction $\operatorname{res}_{C_{2^{n}}}^{D_{2^{n}}}$ is a ring homomorphism, and by the double-coset formulas it commutes with norms and transfers, and with the Weyl action. The operators $V^{n-i}$ and $\tau_{i}$ are described in terms of norms and transfers by Propositions 2.10 and 2.12, and by [HM97, Theorem 3.3] for the usual Witt vectors. It therefore follows that

$$
\operatorname{res}_{C_{2^{n}}}^{D_{2^{n}}} \sigma V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b)=\left[w V^{n-i} \tau_{i} \operatorname{res}_{e}^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}(a \otimes b)\right]=\left[V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a b)\right]
$$

where $\operatorname{res}_{e}^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}$ is the multiplication map of $k \otimes_{S} k$ by [DMPR21, Theorem 5.1]. The proof for the other generators is similar.

Definition 2.15. The fundamental ideal $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}$ of $\pi_{0} \operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$ is the kernel of the ring homomorphism

$$
J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}:=\operatorname{ker}\left(\operatorname{res}_{C_{2^{n}}}^{D_{2^{n}}}: \phi^{n-1}\left(\left(k \otimes_{S} k\right)^{C_{2}}\right) \underset{k \otimes_{S} k}{\times} \phi^{n-1}\left(\left(k \otimes_{S} k\right)^{C_{2}}\right) \longrightarrow \mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{n}\right)}(k) / 2\right)
$$

from Proposition 2.14, for $n \geq 1$, and for $n=0$ it is the kernel of the multiplication map

$$
J_{(1)}:=\operatorname{ker}\left(\operatorname{res}_{e}^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}: k \otimes_{S} k \longrightarrow k=\mathrm{W}_{(1)}(k) / 2\right)
$$

Proposition 2.16. For every $n \geq 0, J_{\left(2^{m}\right)}$ is the subgroup of $\pi_{0} \operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\otimes \mathbb{Z} / 2}$ generated by the elements

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \tau_{n}(a \otimes b)+\tau_{n}(a b \otimes 1) \\
& V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b)+\sigma V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b) \\
& V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b)+V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a b \otimes 1)
\end{aligned}
$$

for all $0 \leq i \leq n-1$ and $a \otimes b \in k \otimes_{S} k$.
Proof. The proof is by induction on $n$. For $n=0$, this is the claim that the kernel of the multiplication map

$$
\mu: k \otimes_{S} k \longrightarrow k
$$

is generated by $a \otimes b+a b \otimes 1$ for $a \otimes b \in k \otimes_{S} k$, which is clear.
Now suppose the claim holds for $n$, and consider the commutative diagram with exact rows
![img-12.jpeg](img-12.jpeg)
where the vertical maps from the top row to the middle row are kernel inclusions. The middle row is exact by [DMP24, Proof of Theorem 4.9], or by the explicit calculation of Theorem 2.7 and Proposition 2.10. Thus, if we find a set of generators for $K$ and show that the map $R$ in the first row is surjective, then $J_{\left(2^{n+1}\right)}$ is generated by the image by $V^{n+1}+\sigma V^{n+1}$ of the generators of $K$, and by a choice of lifts of the generators of $J_{\left(2^{m}\right)}$ given by the inductive assumption. The kernel $K$ consists of those elements $(x, y)$ such that $\mu(x)+\mu(y)$ is a square in $k$. Since every square $c^{2}$ in $k$ is hit by $c \otimes c$ under $\mu, K$ is the subgroup of elements of the form $(x, y)$ where

$$
x=y+c \otimes c+z
$$

for some $c \in k$ and $z \in \operatorname{ker}(\mu)$. Since the kernel of $\mu$ is generated by elements of the form $a \otimes b+a b \otimes 1$, we conclude that $K$ is generated by elements of the form $(a \otimes b, a \otimes b)$, and elements of the form $(a \otimes b+a b \otimes 1+c \otimes c, 0)$. The images of these generators by $V^{n+1}+\sigma V^{n+1}$ are respectively of the form

$$
V^{n+1}(a \otimes b)+\sigma V^{n+1}(a \otimes b)
$$

and

$$
V^{n+1}(a \otimes b+a b \otimes 1+c \otimes c)+\sigma V^{n+1}(0)=V^{n+1}(a \otimes b)+V^{n+1}(a b \otimes 1)+V^{n+1}(c \otimes c)
$$

where $V^{n+1}(c \otimes c)=0$ by Proposition 2.10. It therefore remains to show that by applying $R$ to the elements $\tau_{n+1}(a \otimes b)+\tau_{n+1}(a b \otimes 1), V^{n+1-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b)+\sigma V^{n+1-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b)$ and $V^{n+1-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes$ $b)+V^{n+1-i} \tau_{i}(a b \otimes 1)$, for $1 \leq i \leq n$, we hit all the generators of $J_{\left(2^{m}\right)}$ given by the inductive assumption. This is the case since $R \tau_{i+1}=\tau_{i}, R V^{n+1-i}=V^{n-i} R$, and $R \sigma=\sigma R$, by Theorem 2.7 and Proposition 2.10.

Corollary 2.17. For every $n \geq 0$, the ideal $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}$ is generated, as a $\pi_{0} \operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$-module, by the elements of the form

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \tau_{n}(1 \otimes c)+\tau_{n}(c \otimes 1)=V^{0} \tau_{n}(c \otimes 1)+\sigma V^{0} \tau_{n}(c \otimes 1) \\
& V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b)+\sigma V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b)
\end{aligned}
$$

for all $0 \leq i \leq n-1, a \otimes b \in k \otimes_{S} k$ and $c \in k$. In particular, $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}$ is generated, as a $\pi_{0} \operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$-module, by fixed points for the involution $\sigma$.

Proof. By Proposition 2.16, the corollary follows from the identities

$$
\begin{aligned}
\tau_{n}(a \otimes b)+\tau_{n}(a b \otimes 1) & =\tau_{n}(a \otimes 1) \cdot\left(\tau_{n}(1 \otimes b)+\tau_{n}(b \otimes 1)\right) \\
V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b)+V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a b \otimes 1) & =\left(V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes 1)+\sigma V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(b \otimes 1)\right) \cdot\left(V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(b \otimes 1)+\sigma V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(b \otimes 1)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

which can be easily verified from the definitions.

# 3 Real TR and the de Rham-Witt complex
### 3.1 The Witt complex associated to TRR

Since the operators $F, V, \sigma$ and $R$ of Theorem 2.7 and Proposition 2.10 commute with the restriction map to the Witt vectors modulo 2, they induce maps on the fundamental ideals

$$
F, R: J_{\left(2^{n+1}\right)} \rightarrow J_{\left(2^{n}\right)} \quad, \quad V: J_{\left(2^{n}\right)} \rightarrow J_{\left(2^{n+1}\right)} \quad \text { and } \quad \sigma: J_{\left(2^{n}\right)} \rightarrow J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}
$$

for all $n \geq 0$.
Proposition 3.1. For every integer $q \geq 2$, the maps $F, R, V, \sigma$ above restrict to maps

$$
F, R: J_{\left(2^{n+1}\right)}^{q} \rightarrow J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q} \quad, \quad V: J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q} \rightarrow J_{\left(2^{n+1}\right)}^{q} \quad \text { and } \quad \sigma: J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q} \rightarrow J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q}
$$

Moreover, $1+\sigma$ induces a well-defined map

$$
1+\sigma: J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q} \rightarrow J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q+1}
$$

which satisfies $(1+\sigma)^{2}=0$.
Proof. The claim about $R, F$ and $\sigma$ are clear since these maps are multiplicative. For the map $V$, we employ Corollary 2.17. First suppose that $n \geq 1$, so that the power $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q}$ is additively generated by elements of the form

$$
(x, y) \cdot\left(x_{1}, x_{1}\right) \cdots \cdots\left(x_{q}, x_{q}\right)=\left(x x_{1} \ldots x_{q}, y x_{1} \ldots x_{q}\right)
$$

where $(x, y)$ is a generator of $\pi_{0} \operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$ from Proposition 2.9 , and $\left(x_{l}, x_{l}\right)$ is a generator of $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}$ from Corollary 2.17 , which is diagonal since they are invariant by the Weyl action $\sigma$. Since $V$ is additive, it is sufficient to show that $V$ sends these elements to $J_{\left(2^{n+1}\right)}^{q}$. Now by Proposition 2.10, we have that

$$
\begin{aligned}
V\left(x x_{1} \ldots x_{q}, y x_{1} \ldots x_{q}\right) & =\left((x+y) x_{1} \ldots x_{q}, 0\right) \\
& =(x+y, x+y) \cdot\left(x_{1}, x_{1}\right) \cdots \cdots\left(x_{q-2}, x_{q-2}\right) \cdot\left(x_{q-1}, x_{q-1}\right) \cdot\left(x_{q}, 0\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

The first factor is

$$
(x+y, x+y)=V(x, y)+\sigma V(x, y)
$$

which belongs to $J_{\left(2^{n+1}\right)}$ since it is sent to zero by the restriction map by Proposition 2.14. By Corollary 2.17, each of the factors $\left(x_{1}, x_{1}\right), \ldots,\left(x_{q-1}, x_{q-1}\right)$ is of the form

$$
V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b)+\sigma V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b)
$$

for some $0 \leq i \leq n$, which as an element of $\pi_{0} \operatorname{TRR}^{n+2}(k ; 2)^{\otimes \mathbb{Z} / 2}$ is of the form

$$
V^{n+1-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b)+\sigma V^{n+1-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b)
$$

for $0 \leq i \leq n$, and therefore belongs to $J_{\left(2^{n+1}\right)}$. Thus, it suffices to show that $\left(x_{q-1}, x_{q-1}\right) \cdot\left(x_{q}, 0\right)$ is also in $J_{\left(2^{n+1}\right)}$. But since $\left(x_{q}, x_{q}\right)$ is of the form $V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b)+\sigma V^{n-i} \tau_{i}(a \otimes b)$, we have that $\left(x_{q}, 0\right)$ is a well-defined element of $\pi_{0} \operatorname{TRR}^{n+2}(k ; 2)^{\otimes \mathbb{Z} / 2}$, and since $J_{\left(2^{n+1}\right)}$ is an ideal, $\left(x_{q-1}, x_{q-1}\right) \cdot\left(x_{q}, 0\right)$ indeed belongs to $J_{\left(2^{n+1}\right)}$.

If $n=0$, the ideal $J_{(1)}^{g}$ of $k \otimes_{S} k$ is additively generated by elements of the form $x x_{1} \ldots x_{q}$ with $x \in k \otimes_{S} k$ and $x_{1}, \ldots, x_{q}$ fixed by the involution $w$. Then by Proposition 2.10

$$
V\left(x x_{1} \ldots x_{q}\right)=\left(x x_{1} \ldots x_{q}+w\left(x x_{1} \ldots x_{q}\right), 0\right)=\left((x+w(x)) x_{1} \ldots x_{q}, 0\right)
$$

and one can repeat the argument used in the case $n \geq 1$.
Finally, let us show that $1+\sigma$ sends $J_{(2^{n})}^{g}$ to $J_{(2^{n})}^{q+1}$. By Corollary 2.17, every element of $J_{(2^{n})}^{g}$ is a sum of elements of the form $z \cdot g_{1} \cdots \cdots g_{q}$ with $z \in \pi_{0} \operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\otimes \mathbb{Z} / 2}$ and each $g_{i} \in J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}$ fixed by $\sigma$. Since $1+\sigma$ is additive we only need to show that these elements are sent to $J_{(2^{n})}^{q+1}$. Since $\sigma$ is multiplicative, we have that

$$
(1+\sigma)\left(z \cdot g_{1} \cdots \cdot g_{q}\right)=z \cdot g_{1} \cdots \cdots g_{q}+\sigma(z) \cdot \sigma\left(g_{1}\right) \cdots \cdots \sigma\left(g_{q}\right)=(z+\sigma(z)) \cdot g_{1} \cdots \cdots g_{q}
$$

It therefore suffices to show that $z+\sigma(z)$ belongs to $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}$, which is the case since the restriction map to the Witt vectors modulo 2 is invariant under the action of $\sigma$. Clearly, since $\sigma^{2}$ is the identity, we have that $(1+\sigma)^{2}=0$.

For every $n \geq 0$, let us denote by $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{*} / J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{*}$ the graded ring defined by the quotients $J_{(2^{n})}^{q} / J_{(2^{n})}^{q+1}$ for $q \geq 0$, and by the multiplication of $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}$. We will show that the sequence of graded rings $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{*} / J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{*}$ where $n \geq 0$, equipped with the operators $R, F, V$ and $d:=(1+\sigma)$, define the structure of a 2 -typical Witt complex. We recall its definition, from [Cos08], in the special case where the base ring has characteristic 2. In this case item v) simplifies since $d \log [-1]=0$, and the definition agrees to the one for odd primes from [HM04].
Definition 3.2 ([Cos08]). A 2-typical Witt complex over an $\mathbb{F}_{2}$-algebra $A$ consists of:
i) a graded-commutative pro-graded ring $\left\{E_{n}^{*}, R: E_{n+1}^{*} \rightarrow E_{n}^{*}\right\}_{n \geq 0}$,
ii) A strict map of pro-rings $\lambda: \mathrm{W}_{(\partial \bullet)}(A) \rightarrow E_{\bullet}^{0}$ from the pro-ring of 2-typical Witt vectors of $A$,
iii) a strict map of pro-graded rings

$$
F: E_{\bullet+1}^{*} \longrightarrow E_{\bullet}^{*}
$$

such that $\lambda F=F \lambda$,
iv) a strict map of pro-graded $E_{\bullet}^{*}$-modules

$$
V: F^{*} E_{\bullet}^{*} \longrightarrow E_{\bullet+1}^{*}
$$

such that $\lambda V=V \lambda$ and $F V=2$. The linearity of $V$ means that $V(x) y=V(x F(y))$ for all $x \in E_{n}^{*}$ and $y \in E_{n+1}^{*}$,

v) a strict map of pro-graded abelian groups $d: E_{\bullet}^{*} \rightarrow E_{\bullet}^{*+1}$, which is a derivation, in the sense that

$$
d(x y)=d(x) y+(-1)^{|x|} x d(y)
$$

for all $x, y \in E_{n}^{*}$, and which satisfies the relations

$$
\begin{aligned}
F d V & =d \\
d d & =0 \\
F d \lambda \tau_{n} & =\left(\lambda \tau_{n-1}\right) \cdot\left(d \lambda \tau_{n-1}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\tau_{n}: A \rightarrow \mathrm{~W}_{\left(2^{n}\right)}(A)$ is the Teichmüller map sending $a$ to $(a, 0, \ldots, 0)$.
Before showing that the graded ring defined by the ideals $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}$ admits the structure of a Witt-complex, let us point out that since the map $\operatorname{res}_{C_{2^{n}}}^{D_{2^{n}}}$ is surjective by Propositions 2.14, it induces an isomorphism

$$
J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{0} / J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}=\pi_{0} \operatorname{TRR}^{n+1}(k ; 2)^{\# \mathbb{Z} / 2} / \operatorname{ker}\left(\operatorname{res}_{C_{2^{n}}}^{D_{2^{n}}}\right) \xrightarrow{\#} \pi_{0} \operatorname{TR}^{n+1}(k ; 2) / 2 \cong \mathrm{~W}_{\left(2^{n}\right)}(k) / 2
$$

where the last isomorphism is from [HM97, Theorem F].
Proposition 3.3. The sequence of graded rings $\left\{J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{*} / J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{*}\right\}_{n \geqslant 0}$ equipped with the operators $R, F, V$ and $d:=(1+\sigma)$ from Proposition 3.1, and the quotient maps

$$
\lambda: \mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{n}\right)}(k) \longrightarrow \mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{n}\right)}(k) / 2 \cong J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{0} / J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}
$$

defines a 2-typical Witt complex over the field $k$ of characteristic 2 .
Proof. First of all, the maps $R, F, V$ and $d:=(1+\sigma)$ are well-defined on the quotients of the powers of the ideals by Proposition 3.1. Axioms i)-iv) of Definition 3.2 follow immediately from either the fact that $F, V$ and $\operatorname{res}_{C_{2^{n}}}^{D_{2^{n}}}$ are induced from the maps of a Mackey functor, or from their explicit formulas from Theorem 2.7 and Propositions 2.10 and 2.14. This is except from the identity $F V=2$ (which in our case is zero), since by these arguments we only know that $F V=1+\sigma$. However, for every $x \in J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q}$, we have that

$$
F V(x)=x+\sigma(x)
$$

belongs to $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q+1}$ by Proposition 3.1, and it is therefore indeed zero in $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q} / J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q+1}$.
Let us show axiom v). To see that $d$ satisfies the Leibniz rule, let $x \in J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q} / J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q+1}$ and $y \in J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q^{\prime}} / J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q^{\prime}+1}$, and let us calculate

$$
\begin{aligned}
d(x y)+d(x) y+x d(y) & =x y+\sigma(x) \sigma(y)+(x+\sigma(x)) y+x(y+\sigma(y)) \\
& =x y+\sigma(x) \sigma(y)+\sigma(x) y+x \sigma(y)=(x+\sigma(x))(y+\sigma(y)) \\
& =d(x) d(y)
\end{aligned}
$$

Since $d(x)$ belongs to $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q+1}$ and $d(y)$ to $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q^{\prime}+1}$ by Proposition 3.1, we have that $d(x) d(y)$ belongs to $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q+q^{\prime}+2}$, and therefore it vanishes in $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q+q^{\prime}+1} / J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q+q^{\prime}+2}$.

Let us now verify the last three identities involving $d$ in axiom v). For the first one, let $x \in J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q} / J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q+1}$. Then

$$
F d V(x)=F V(x)+F \sigma V(x)=F V(x)=(1+\sigma)(x)=d(x)
$$

in $J_{(2^{n})}^{q+1} / J_{(2^{n})}^{q+2}$, where $F \sigma V(x)=0$ by the double coset formula (or by direct calculation). For the second identity, we have that

$$
d^{2}=(1+\sigma)^{2}=1+2 \sigma+\sigma^{2}=2+2 \sigma=0
$$

since $\sigma$ has order 2. Finally, for the third one, let $a \in k=\mathrm{W}_{(1)}(k)$. On the one hand, by Proposition 2.14,

$$
\begin{aligned}
F d \lambda \tau_{n}(a) & =F d \tau_{n}(a \otimes 1)=F\left(\tau_{n}(a \otimes 1)+\sigma \tau_{n}(a \otimes 1)\right) \\
& =\tau_{n}(a \otimes 1)+\sigma \tau_{n}(a \otimes 1)=\left(a^{2^{n}} \otimes 1+a^{2^{n}-1} \otimes a, a^{2^{n}-1} \otimes a+a^{2^{n}} \otimes 1\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where the third equality holds by the formula for $F$ of Theorem 2.7. On the other hand

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left(\lambda \tau_{n-1}(a)\right) \cdot\left(d \lambda \tau_{n-1}(a)\right)=\tau_{n-1}(a \otimes 1) \cdot\left(\tau_{n-1}(a \otimes 1)+\sigma \tau_{n-1}(a \otimes 1)\right) \\
& =\left(a^{2^{n-1}} \otimes 1, a^{2^{n-1}-1} \otimes a\right) \cdot\left(a^{2^{n-1}} \otimes 1+a^{2^{n-1}-1} \otimes a, a^{2^{n-1}-1} \otimes a+a^{2^{n-1}} \otimes 1\right) \\
& =\left(a^{2^{n}} \otimes 1+a^{2^{n}-1} \otimes a, a^{2^{n}-2} \otimes a^{2}+a^{2^{n}-1} \otimes a\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

and these are equal since we are tensoring over $S$.

# 3.2 The Milnor conjecture for the de Rham-Witt complex 

Let us endow the sequence $J_{(2 \bullet)}^{*} / J_{(2 \bullet)}^{n+1}$ with the structure of a 2 -typical Witt complex of Proposition 3.3. We recall that, by definition, the 2-typical de Rham-Witt complex $\mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)} \Omega_{k}^{*}$ of $k$ is the initial object in the category of 2-typical Witt complexes over $k$ (see [Cos08] and [HM04]). Thus, there is a unique map of 2-typical Witt complexes

$$
\mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)} \Omega_{k}^{*} \longrightarrow J_{(2 \bullet)}^{*} / J_{(2 \bullet)}^{n+1}
$$

Let us denote by $\mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)} \Omega_{k}^{*} / 2$ the degreewise cokernel of the multiplication by 2 map. Since all the maps defining the structure of a Witt complex are additive, this is again a Witt-complex, where the map

$$
\mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)}(k) \longrightarrow \mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)} \Omega_{k}^{0} / 2=\mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)}(k) / 2
$$

is the quotient map. Since 2 vanishes in $J_{(2 \bullet)}^{*} / J_{(2 \bullet)}^{n+1}$, the unique map above descends to a unique map of Witt-complexes

$$
u: \mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)} \Omega_{k}^{*} / 2 \longrightarrow J_{(2 \bullet)}^{*} / J_{(2 \bullet)}^{n+1}
$$

Theorem 3.4. The unique map of Witt-complexes $u: \mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)} \Omega_{k}^{*} / 2 \rightarrow J_{(2 \bullet)}^{*} / J_{(2 \bullet)}^{n+1}$ is an isomorphism.

Remark 3.5. Let us discuss a few special cases of this theorem. For $*=0$, the unique map $u$ is by construction the isomorphism

$$
\lambda: \mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)} \Omega_{k}^{0} / 2=\mathrm{W}_{(2 \bullet)}(k) / 2 \xrightarrow{\mathrm{~g}} \pi_{0} \operatorname{TR}(k ; 2) / 2 \cong \pi_{0} \operatorname{TRR}^{\bullet+1}(k ; 2)^{\oplus \mathbb{Z} / 2} / J_{(2 \bullet)}
$$

where the arrow is the isomorphism of [HM97, Theorem F].
On the other hand, for $\bullet=0$, the map $u$ is the unique map of commutative differential graded algebras

$$
\mathrm{W}_{(1)} \Omega_{k}^{*} / 2=\Omega_{k}^{*} \longrightarrow J_{(1)}^{*} / J_{(1)}^{n+1}
$$

This is well-known to be an isomorphism, as claimed in [Kat82] (see e.g. [Ara20] for a proof, which is also recasted in Lemma 3.6 below). In particular, for $*=1$, this is equivalent to the fact that, since $k$ has characteristic 2 , a $\mathbb{Z}$-linear derivation out of $k$ is automatically $S$-linear (where we recall that $S \leq k$ is the subfield of squares).

The rest of the section is dedicated to the proof of Theorem 3.4. The proof is by induction on $n$, by means of the exact sequences

$$
\Omega_{k}^{q} \oplus \Omega_{k}^{q-1} \xrightarrow{V^{n}+d V^{m}} \mathrm{~W}_{\left\{2^{n}\right\}} \Omega_{k}^{q} / 2 \xrightarrow{R} \mathrm{~W}_{\left\{2^{n-1}\right\}} \Omega_{k}^{q} / 2 \longrightarrow 0
$$

from [Cos08, Lemma 3.5], where $n, q \geq 1$.
The base case for the induction $n=1$ seems to be well-known to the experts, and is used without proof in [Kat82]. We recall the argument from [Ara20, Fact 1] for the reader's convenience, and to introduce some notation that we will use in the proof of the induction step.
Lemma 3.6 ([Ara20]). The unique map $u: \Omega_{k}^{*} \longrightarrow J_{(1)}^{*} / J_{(1)}^{*+1}$ of commutative differential graded algebras is an isomorphism.

Proof. For every $a \in k$, let us denote $\Delta(a):=1 \otimes a+a \otimes 1 \in k \otimes_{S} k$. We note that the map $u$ is necessarily given by the formula

$$
u\left(a d a_{1} \ldots d a_{q}\right):=a \Delta\left(a_{1}\right) \cdots \cdots \Delta\left(a_{q}\right)
$$

In order to show that this is an isomorphism, we choose suitable bases of the source and target as $k$-vector spaces. Let $\left\{x_{i}\right\}_{i \in I}$ be a 2-basis of $k$. We recall that this is a set of elements of $k$ whose differentials $\left\{d x_{i}\right\}_{i \in I}$ form a basis of the $k$-vector space $\Omega_{k}^{1}$ or, equivalently, such that the elements

$$
x^{\xi}:=\prod_{i \in \xi} x_{i}

Moreover, this element is by assumption in $J_{\left(2^{n}\right)}^{q+1}$. By applying Lemma 3.8, the first component $\sum_{\substack{\xi \in I \\|\xi|=q}} \Delta\left(\lambda_{\xi}\right) \Delta(x)^{\xi}$ in fact belongs to $J_{\{1\}}^{q+2}$. Again by Lemma 3.7, we find that

$$
c=V^{n}(a)=V^{n-1} V\left(\sum_{\substack{\xi \in I \\|\xi|=q}} \lambda_{\xi}(d x)^{\xi}\right)=0

in $\left(\mathrm{W}_{\left(2^{n}\right)} \Omega_{k}^{q}\right) / 2$, proving that $u_{n}$ is injective.

# 3.3 The Milnor conjecture and TCR 

Let us recall that the 2 -typical topological cyclic homology spectrum $\mathrm{TC}(k ; 2)$ of $k$ can be defined as the equaliser

$$
\mathrm{TC}(k ; 2) \longrightarrow \mathrm{TR}(k ; 2) \stackrel{\text { id }}{\Longrightarrow} \mathrm{TR}(k ; 2)
$$

of the identity and the Frobenius map of $\operatorname{TR}(k ; 2)$. Let us denote $\mathrm{W}_{\{2 \infty\}} \Omega_{k}^{*}$ the limit of $\mathrm{W}_{\left\{2^{n}\right\}} \Omega_{k}^{*}$ over the map $R$, and define $\nu_{*}^{d R W / 2}(k ; 2)$ and $e_{*}^{*} R W / 2}(k ; 2)$ respectively as the equaliser and coequaliser of the parallel group homomorphisms

$$
\nu_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2) \longrightarrow\left(\mathrm{W}_{\left\{2^{\infty}\right\}} \Omega_{k}^{*}\right) / 2 \stackrel{\text { id }}{\Longrightarrow}\left(\mathrm{W}_{\left\{2^{\infty}\right\}} \Omega_{k}^{*}\right) / 2 \longrightarrow \epsilon_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2)
$$

Then, since the parallel arrows are ring homomorphisms, $\nu_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2)$ is a graded ring, and $\epsilon_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2)$ is a graded $\nu_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2)$-module (where the action on the latter is defined via either of the maps id or $F$ ). We now prove a version of the Milnor conjecture for $\nu_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2)$ and $\epsilon_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2)$, which describes these in terms of the graded ring associated to the kernel of the restriction map

$$
K:=\operatorname{ker}\left(\operatorname{res}_{c}^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}: \pi_{0} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \longrightarrow\left(\pi_{0} \operatorname{TC}(k ; 2)\right)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2} / \operatorname{Im}(1+w)\right)
$$

where the involution on $\pi_{0} \mathrm{TC}(k ; 2)$ is induced by the involution underlying the $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-spectrum $\operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)$. The restriction map is defined as we did at the beginning of $\S 2.3$. Let us also define the $\pi_{0} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$-module

$$
T_{-1}:=\pi_{-1} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}
$$

so that the quotients $K^{*} T_{-1} / K^{*+1} T_{-1}$ form a graded $K^{*} / K^{*+1}$-module.
Theorem 3.9. Let $k$ be a field of characteristic 2. There is an isomorphism of graded rings

$$
\nu_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2) \cong K^{*} / K^{*+1}
$$

and an isomorphism of graded $K^{*} / K^{*+1}$-modules

$$
\epsilon_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2) \cong K^{*} T_{-1} / K^{*+1} T_{-1}
$$

Proof. Let $\nu^{*}(k)$ and be $\epsilon^{*}(k)$ be respectively the equaliser and coequaliser of the projection map and the inverse Cartier operator

$$
\nu^{*}(k) \longrightarrow \Omega_{k}^{*} \underset{C^{-1}}{\Longleftrightarrow} \Omega_{k}^{*} / d\left(\Omega_{k}^{*-1}\right) \longrightarrow \epsilon^{*}(k)
$$

The map $R$ of the de Rham-Witt complex induces multiplicative maps $\nu_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2) \rightarrow \nu^{*}(k)$ and $\epsilon_{d R W / 2}^{*}(k ; 2) \rightarrow \epsilon^{*}(k)$, which are isomorphisms by the proof of [CMM21, Proposition 2.26]. Moreover, by [Kat82, Theorem (2)], the graded ring associated to the fundamental ideal $I$ of the symmetric Witt group is isomorphic to $\nu^{*}(k)$, and the graded module $I^{*} \mathrm{~W}^{q}(k) / I^{*+1} \mathrm{~W}^{q}(k)$ to $\epsilon^{*}(k)$. Thus, since [Kat82, Theorem (1)] and Corollary 2.5 identify $\mathrm{W}^{*}(k)$ and $\pi_{0} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$, as rings, with the equaliser of

$$
\left(k \otimes_{S} k\right)^{C_{2}} \underset{\phi}{\stackrel{\pi}{\rightrightarrows}}\left(k \otimes_{S} k\right)^{C_{2}} / \operatorname{Im}(1+w)
$$

and $\mathrm{W}^{q}(k)$ and $T_{-1}$, as modules, with their coequaliser, it suffices to show that $I$ and $K$ correspond to the same ideal under these identifications.

For the symmetric Witt group, the isomorphism with the equaliser is given by the unique additive map that sends the rank 1 form $(a)$, with $a \in k^{*}$, to $a^{-1} \otimes a$. For $\pi_{0} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$, it is induced by the map

$$
\pi_{0} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \xrightarrow{R} \pi_{0} \operatorname{TRR}^{2}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \xrightarrow{c} \pi_{0}\left(\operatorname{THR}(k)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}\right)^{C_{2}}
$$

followed by the identification of the target with $\left(k \otimes_{S} k\right)^{C_{2}}$ from Proposition 2.3. Let us note that, after including the fixed points into $k \otimes_{S} k$, this is the map

$$
\pi_{0} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \xrightarrow{R} \pi_{0} \operatorname{THR}(k)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2} \cong k \otimes_{S} k
$$

where the isomorphism is from [DMPR21, Theorem 5.1] (there it is stated for the fixed points, but since the transfer map of $k$ is zero the isomorphism descends to the geometric fixed points). Thus, in order to compare $I$ and $K$, it suffices to show that, under the isomorphism of Corollary 2.5 , the restriction map from $\pi_{0} \operatorname{TCR}(k ; 2)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}$ to $\left(\pi_{0} \mathrm{TC}(k ; 2)\right)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2} / \operatorname{Im}(1+w)$ sends $a^{-1} \otimes a$ to 1. # A The trace map for rings with involution 

Let us finish the paper with a construction of a $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-equivariant lift of the trace map tr: $\mathrm{K} \rightarrow$ $\mathrm{TC}(-; p)$, for every prime $p$. The trace was first constructed by Bökstedt-Hsiang-Madsen in [BHM93] as a natural transformation $\mathrm{K} \rightarrow \mathrm{TC}$ on the category of ring spectra. This construction has been extended to various settings, most notably as a natural transformation of functors from stable infinity categories, see e.g. [BGT14].

A $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-equivariant extension of this map as a natural transformation $\mathrm{KR} \rightarrow \mathrm{TCR}$ of functors from Poincaré categories will appear in forthcoming work of Harpaz-Nikolaus-Shah [HNS21]. For the purpose of this article, it will be more than sufficient to define the $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-equivariant trace map on the category of discrete rings with involution. We will give a construction in line with the construction of the Dennis trace as carried out in [Mad94, §2.6]. After restricting down to THR this construction agrees with the one from [DO19], which was defined for ring spectra with involution.

Let $A$ be a ring with involution $w: A^{v p} \rightarrow A$, and $\mathrm{GL}_{n}(A)$ the group of invertible $n \times n$ matrices with the involution that sends $M$ to $M^{*}:=w(M)^{T}$, where $(-)^{T}$ denotes the matrix transposition and $w$ is applied to $M$ entrywise. The set of fixed points of $\mathrm{GL}_{n}(A)$ is the set of symmetric matrices

$$
\mathrm{GL}_{n}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}=\left\{M \in \mathrm{GL}_{n}(k) \mid M^{*}=M\right\}
$$

and $\mathrm{GL}_{n}(A)$ acts on it by $g \cdot M=g M g^{*}$. We let $B^{\sigma} \mathrm{GL}_{n}(A)$ be the classifying space $B \mathrm{GL}_{n}(A)$ with the involution of [BF84, Proposition 1.1.3]. Its $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-fixed-points space is the bar construction of the action of $\mathrm{GL}_{n}(A)$ on $\mathrm{GL}_{n}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}$ above (see also [DO19, §2.1] for the details). For the purpose of this paper, we define $\operatorname{KR}(A)$ to be the $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-equivariant group-completion of the $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-equivariant $E_{\infty}$-monoid with involution

$$
\coprod_{n \geq 0} B^{\sigma} \mathrm{GL}_{n}(A)
$$

where the monoid operation is induced by the direct sum of matrices. This is in fact the classifying space of the symmetric monoidal category with duality of finite dimensional free $A$ modules, and therefore indeed a $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-equivariant $E_{\infty}$-monoid. By construction, $\pi_{0}\left(\operatorname{KR}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right)$ is the group-completion of the commutative monoid

$$
\coprod_{n \geq 0} \pi_{0}\left(\left(B^{\sigma} \mathrm{GL}_{n}(A)\right)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right) \cong \coprod_{n \geq 0} \mathrm{GL}_{n}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2} / \mathrm{GL}_{n}(A)
$$

which is the Grothendieck-Witt group $\mathrm{GW}^{*}(A)$ of symmetric forms of free $A$-modules. The transfer map is induced by the functor that sends a free module of rank $n$ to the hyperbolic matrix of size $2 n$, and therefore $\pi_{0}\left(\operatorname{KR}(A)^{\# \mathbb{Z} / 2}\right)$ is the symmetric Witt group $W^{s}(A)$ (again of free $A$-modules).

Let us also recall from [DMPR21, Theorem 5.1] that there is an isomorphism of abelian groups

$$
\pi_{0}\left(\operatorname{THR}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right) \cong\left(A^{\mathbb{Z} / 2} \otimes A^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right) / T
$$

where $A^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}$ is the subgroup of fixed points of the involution $w$, and the quotient is by the subgroup $T$ generated by the elements of the form (i) and (ii) from [DMPR21, Theorem 5.1]. In particular, for $A=k$ a ring of characteristic 2 with trivial involution, this is $k \otimes_{S} k$, and since the transfer map $(a+w(a)) \otimes 1$ of [DMPR21, Theorem 5.1] is in this case zero, we have as well that $\pi_{0}(\operatorname{THR}(k)^{\phi \mathbb{Z} / 2}) \cong k \otimes_{S} k$.
Proposition A.1. Let $A$ be a ring with involution. For every prime $p$, there is a map of $\mathbb{Z} / 2$ spectra $\operatorname{tr}: \mathrm{KR}(A) \rightarrow \operatorname{TCR}(A ; p)$ which forgets to the $K$-theoretic trace map of [BHM93]. The composite

$$
\mathrm{GW}^{s}(A)=\pi_{0}\left(\mathrm{KR}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right) \xrightarrow{\mathrm{tr}} \pi_{0}\left(\operatorname{TCR}(A ; 2)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right) \xrightarrow{R} \pi_{0}\left(\operatorname{THR}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right) \cong\left(A^{\mathbb{Z} / 2} \otimes A^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right) / T
$$

sends the element of $\mathrm{GW}^{s}(A)$ represented by a symmetric form $x$ on $A^{\otimes n}$ to

$$
\operatorname{tr}(x)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\left(x^{-1}\right)_{i i} \otimes x_{i i}-\left(x^{-1}\right)_{i i} x_{i i} \otimes 1\right)+n \otimes 1
$$

where $x_{i i}$ are the entries of the matrix of $x$ for the standard basis of $A^{\otimes n}$, and $x^{-1}$ denotes the inverse matrix.

We define the trace map from maps of $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-spaces

$$

For larger values of $n$ we need to determine the isomorphism

$$
m:\left(\mathrm{M}_{n}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2} \otimes \mathrm{M}_{n}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right) / T \xrightarrow{\circ}\left(A^{\mathbb{Z} / 2} \otimes A^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right) / T
$$

Let us decompose a symmetric matrix $M \in \mathrm{M}_{n}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}$ as $M=\sum_{i=1}^{n} M_{i i} e_{i i}+\sum_{1 \leq i<j \leq n}\left(M_{i j} e_{i j}+\right.$ $\left.w\left(M_{i j}\right) e_{j i}\right)$ where $e_{i j}$ is the canonical basis element with 1 in the entry $(i, j)$ and with all the other entries equal to zero. By regarding the abelian group with involution $\mathrm{M}_{n}(A)$ as a Mackey functor, we can then write the fixed point $M$ as

$$
M=\sum_{i=1}^{n} M_{i i} e_{i i}+\sum_{1 \leq i<j \leq n} \operatorname{tran}\left(M_{i j} e_{i j}\right)
$$

where tran denotes the transfer map of the Mackey functor, which sends a matrix $N$ to $N+N^{*}$. By applying the same decomposition to a second fixed point $M^{\prime} \in \mathrm{M}_{n}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}$ we find that

$$
\begin{aligned}
M^{\prime} \otimes M & =\sum_{l, i=1}^{n} M_{l l}^{\prime} e_{l l} \otimes M_{i i} e_{i i}+\sum_{l=1}^{n} \sum_{1 \leq i<j \leq n} M_{l l}^{\prime} e_{l l} \otimes \operatorname{tran}\left(M_{i j} e_{i j}\right) \\
& +\sum_{1 \leq l<k \leq n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} \operatorname{tran}\left(M_{l k}^{\prime} e_{l k}\right) \otimes M_{i i} e_{i i}+\sum_{1 \leq l<k \leq n} \sum_{1 \leq i<j \leq n}^{n} \operatorname{tran}\left(M_{l k}^{\prime} e_{l k}\right) \otimes \operatorname{tran}\left(M_{i j} e_{i j}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

By the relation (ii) of [DMPR21, Theorem 5.1] defining the subgroup $T$, this is equivalent to

$$
\begin{aligned}
M^{\prime} \otimes M & =\sum_{l, i=1}^{n} M_{l l}^{\prime} e_{l l} \otimes M_{i i} e_{i i}+\sum_{l=1}^{n} \sum_{1 \leq i<j \leq n} \operatorname{tran}\left(M_{l l}^{\prime} e_{l l} M_{i j} e_{i j}\right) \otimes 1 \\
& +\sum_{1 \leq l<k \leq n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} 1 \otimes \operatorname{tran}\left(M_{l k}^{\prime} e_{l k} M_{i i} e_{i i}\right)+\sum_{1 \leq l<k \leq n} \sum_{1 \leq i<j \leq n} \operatorname{tran}\left(M_{l k}^{\prime} e_{l k}\left(M_{i j} e_{i j}+w\left(M_{i j}\right) e_{j i}\right)\right) \otimes 1 \\
& =\sum_{l, i=1}^{n} M_{l l}^{\prime} e_{l l} \otimes M_{i i} e_{i i}+\sum_{1 \leq i<j \leq n} \operatorname{tran}\left(M_{i i}^{\prime} M_{i j} e_{i j}\right) \otimes 1+\sum_{1 \leq l<k \leq n} 1 \otimes \operatorname{tran}\left(M_{l k}^{\prime} M_{k k} e_{l k}\right) \\
& +\sum_{1 \leq l<k<j \leq n} \operatorname{tran}\left(M_{l k}^{\prime} M_{k j} e_{l j}\right) \otimes 1+\sum_{1 \leq l, i<k \leq n} \operatorname{tran}\left(M_{l k}^{\prime} w\left(M_{i k}\right) e_{l i}\right) \otimes 1
\end{aligned}
$$

where the last equality follows from carrying out the matrix multiplication on the canonical basis. Again by [DMPR21, Theorem 5.1], the transfer map of the Mackey functor $\underline{Z}_{0} \operatorname{THR}\left(\mathrm{M}_{n}(A)\right)$ sends the equivalence class of a matrix $M$ in $\pi_{0} \operatorname{THH}\left(\mathrm{M}_{n}(A)\right) \cong \mathrm{M}_{n}(A) /\left[\mathrm{M}_{n}(A), \mathrm{M}_{n}(A)\right]$, to $1 \otimes \operatorname{tran}(M)=\operatorname{tran}(M) \otimes 1$ in $\left(\mathrm{M}_{n}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2} \otimes \mathrm{M}_{n}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right) / T$. The map $m$ from [DMPR21, Theorem 4.9] is a map of $\mathbb{Z} / 2$-spectra, and therefore it commutes with the transfer. Moreover, since the underlying map of spectra is the trace map of [BHM93], in $\pi_{0}$ it sends a matrix to its trace, and therefore the terms involving $e_{i j}$ vanish for $i \neq j$. We then find that

$$
m\left(M^{\prime} \otimes M\right)=\sum_{l, i=1}^{n} m\left(M_{l l}^{\prime} e_{l l} \otimes M_{i i} e_{i i}\right)+\sum_{1 \leq l<k \leq n} \operatorname{tran}\left(M_{l k}^{\prime} w\left(M_{l k}\right)\right) \otimes 1
$$

in $\left(A^{\mathbb{Z} / 2} \otimes A^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}\right) / T$. By the definition of $m$ of [DMPR21, Proof of Theorem 4.9], it sends $e_{i j} \otimes e_{l k}$ to 1 if $j=l$ and $k=i$, and to zero otherwise. Thus

$$
m\left(M^{\prime} \otimes M\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{n} M_{i i}^{\prime} \otimes M_{i i}+\sum_{1 \leq l<k \leq n} \operatorname{tran}\left(M_{l k}^{\prime} w\left(M_{l k}\right)\right) \otimes 1
$$

Since $M$ is symmetric, i.e. $w\left(M_{l k}\right)=M_{k l}$, we may write this expression as

$$
m\left(M^{\prime} \otimes M\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{n} M_{i i}^{\prime} \otimes M_{i i}+\operatorname{tr}\left(M^{\prime} M\right) \otimes 1-\sum_{i=1}^{n} M_{i i}^{\prime} M_{i i} \otimes 1
$$

where $\operatorname{tr}$ denotes the usual trace of a matrix. When $M^{\prime} \otimes M=x^{-1} \otimes x$ for some $x \in \mathrm{GL}_{n}(A)^{\mathbb{Z} / 2}$, this gives the formula we wanted.

abstract:
We describe the modulo $2$ de Rham-Witt complex of a field of characteristic
$2$, in terms of the powers of the augmentation ideal of the
$\mathbb{Z}/2$-geometric fixed points of real topological restriction homology
TRR. This is analogous to the conjecture of Milnor, proved by Kato for fields
of characteristic $2$, which describes the modulo $2$ Milnor K-theory in terms
of the powers of the augmentation ideal of the Witt group of symmetric forms.
Our proof provides a somewhat explicit description of these objects, as well as
a calculation of the homotopy groups of the geometric fixed points of TRR and
of real topological cyclic homology, for all fields.
